---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import FAQAccordion from "@/components/FAQAccordion";
import { buildBreadcrumbSchema, buildArticleSchema, buildFaqSchema } from "@/lib/schema";

const title = "Sustainable Living Near Green School Bali: Inside Eco Village Sibang";
const description =
  "What sustainable living actually looks like in Eco Village Sibang: walkability, community, and homes built from natural materials, 8 minutes from Green School Bali.";
const image = "https://ecovillabali.com/images/blog-family-exploring-sustainable-living.webp";
const path = "/blog/sustainable-living-bali-eco-village-sibang";

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "What is sustainable living?",
    answer:
      "Sustainable living involves making choices that reduce environmental impact while supporting long-term wellbeing, community resilience and responsible use of resources.",
  },
  {
    question: "Why do Green School families choose Eco Village Sibang?",
    answer:
      "Many families choose Eco Village Sibang because of its strong community, sustainable design principles and convenient location just 8 minutes from Green School Bali.",
  },
  {
    question: "Is Eco Village Sibang within walking distance of Green School Bali?",
    answer:
      "Yes. Eco Village Sibang is approximately 700 meters from Green School Bali and can be reached in around 8 minutes on foot or a few minutes by bicycle.",
  },
  {
    question: "Are sustainable homes comfortable in Bali?",
    answer:
      "Yes. Modern sustainable homes often use passive cooling, natural ventilation and climate-responsive design to create comfortable living environments without excessive energy consumption.",
  },
  {
    question: "What makes a community sustainable?",
    answer:
      "A sustainable community balances environmental responsibility, social connection and long-term resilience while supporting a high quality of life for residents.",
  },
  {
    question: "Is Eco Village Sibang suitable for families?",
    answer:
      "Eco Village Sibang was designed with family living in mind and is home to many Green School families who value community, nature and walkability.",
  },
];

const articleSchema = buildArticleSchema({
  headline: "Sustainable Living Near Green School Bali: Inside Eco Village Sibang",
  description,
  path,
  image,
  datePublished: "2026-06-15",
  dateModified: "2026-07-13",
});
const breadcrumbSchema = buildBreadcrumbSchema("Blog", "/blog");
const faqSchema = buildFaqSchema(faqs);
const cspNonce = Astro.locals.cspNonce;
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} image={image}>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline nonce={cspNonce} set:html={JSON.stringify(articleSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline nonce={cspNonce} set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline nonce={cspNonce} set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <div class="pt-8">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-16">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-accent transition-colors mb-8 inline-block">
        &larr; Back to Blog
      </a>

      <header class="mb-8">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-4">
          <span>June 2026</span>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <span>Sustainability</span>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <span>11 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-primary mb-4">
          Sustainable Living Near Green School Bali: Inside Eco Village Sibang
        </h1>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground">
          By <a href="/about" class="text-accent hover:underline">Oscar Kolthoff</a>, former Eco Village Sibang resident and Green School Bali parent
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="space-y-5 text-foreground/90 leading-relaxed">
        <p>For many families, the journey begins with Green School Bali.</p>

        <p>
          What attracts them initially is often the school's innovative approach to education, sustainability and
          experiential learning. But as families spend more time exploring the area, another question naturally
          emerges: what would it actually be like to live according to those same values every day?
        </p>

        <p>
          Sustainable living is often associated with solar panels, bamboo architecture and eco-friendly
          technologies. While those elements certainly play a role, the reality is much broader. For many families,
          sustainability is just as much about community, children's independence, walkability, food, connection to
          nature and a slower pace of life.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is one of the reasons why Eco Village Sibang has become a popular choice among Green School families.
          Located just an 8-minute walk from campus, it offers an opportunity to align daily life with many of the
          same principles that attracted families to Green School in the first place.
        </p>

        <img
          src="/images/blog-children-natural-playground.webp"
          alt="Children playing in natural playground"
          width="1200"
          height="800"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
          class="w-full max-w-2xl rounded-lg mx-auto my-8"
        />

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">What Sustainable Living Really Means</h2>

        <p>
          Sustainability is often misunderstood as a collection of environmental features. Solar panels, rainwater
          systems and natural building materials are important, but they are only part of the picture.
        </p>

        <p>A truly sustainable lifestyle considers three interconnected elements: environmental, social, and economic sustainability.</p>

        <p>
          Environmental sustainability focuses on reducing environmental impact through responsible use of
          resources, energy efficiency and regenerative practices. Social sustainability is about creating
          communities where people know their neighbours, children can move around safely and families feel
          connected to one another. Economic sustainability focuses on creating systems that can thrive over the
          long term rather than relying on excessive consumption or waste.
        </p>

        <p>The most successful communities combine all three.</p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">Why Green School Families Often Seek a Different Lifestyle</h2>

        <p>Families rarely move across the world solely because of a school. In many cases, Green School simply becomes the catalyst for a broader lifestyle change.</p>

        <p>
          Parents are often looking for more time outdoors, less time in traffic, stronger community connections,
          greater independence for their children, a healthier relationship with nature, and a slower, more
          intentional pace of life.
        </p>

        <p>
          Many families arrive in Bali after years of busy urban living. They are successful professionals,
          entrepreneurs or remote workers who have reached a point where quality of life becomes more important
          than convenience or status. Green School provides an educational environment that reflects these values.
          Naturally, many families begin searching for a living environment that does the same.
        </p>

        <img
          src="/images/blog-family-exploring-sustainable-living.webp"
          alt="Family exploring sustainable living"
          width="1200"
          height="800"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
          class="w-full max-w-2xl rounded-lg mx-auto my-8"
        />

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">Inside Eco Village Sibang</h2>

        <p>
          Eco Village Sibang was created around a simple idea: how can modern families live comfortably while
          reducing their environmental footprint and increasing their connection to community and nature? The
          result is a neighbourhood where sustainability is not treated as an afterthought.
        </p>

        <p>
          Many homes incorporate natural building materials, reclaimed timber, bamboo elements, passive cooling
          design, thick earthen walls, natural landscaping, and water-conscious systems.
        </p>

        <p>
          The goal is not to sacrifice comfort. The goal is to create homes that work with Bali's climate rather
          than constantly fighting against it. This approach often results in homes that feel naturally cooler,
          quieter and more connected to their surroundings.
        </p>

        <p>
          But perhaps more importantly, the village itself is designed around people rather than cars. Families
          walk. Children cycle. Neighbours know one another. Community life happens naturally.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">The Sustainability of Daily Life</h2>

        <p>
          One of the biggest surprises for many families is that the most meaningful sustainable changes are often
          the simplest. Instead of spending hours each week commuting, children walk or cycle to school. Instead of
          organising play dates across town, children meet friends who live just a few minutes away. Instead of
          spending weekends escaping traffic, families spend time gardening, exploring nature or participating in
          community events.
        </p>

        <p>
          These small shifts create a different rhythm of life. A typical morning might begin with a short walk
          through the neighbourhood to Green School. Parents often stop for coffee with other families after
          drop-off. Children become familiar with the people around them and develop a stronger sense of
          independence.
        </p>

        <p>These experiences may seem simple, but they significantly impact quality of life over time.</p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">Why Walkability Matters More Than Most Families Expect</h2>

        <p>
          When families first consider relocating to Bali, walkability is rarely at the top of their list. After
          living near Green School, many realise it becomes one of the most valuable aspects of daily life.
        </p>

        <p>
          Eco Village Sibang is located approximately 700 meters from Green School Bali, making it possible to
          reach campus in around 8 minutes on foot or just a few minutes by bicycle. The benefits go far beyond
          convenience: less time in traffic, greater independence for children, more spontaneous social
          interactions, reduced transportation costs, lower environmental impact, and stronger community
          connections.
        </p>

        <p>
          Children who can safely walk or cycle to school often develop confidence and independence earlier than
          those who rely on daily car transportation. For many families, this becomes one of the most appreciated
          aspects of living near Green School.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">Building a Community Rather Than Just Owning a Home</h2>

        <p>A house is important. A community is often what determines whether a family truly feels at home.</p>

        <p>
          One of the defining characteristics of Eco Village Sibang is the strength of its community. Many
          residents share similar values around education, sustainability, family life, health and wellbeing, and
          international living. This naturally creates opportunities for connection.
        </p>

        <p>
          Families support one another during relocations. Parents share recommendations and advice. Children form
          friendships that extend beyond the school environment. Community dinners, workshops and informal
          gatherings help strengthen these relationships over time.
        </p>

        <p>
          For families moving far from their home countries, this sense of belonging can be just as valuable as the
          physical home itself.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">Can Sustainable Living Also Be Comfortable?</h2>

        <p>One of the most common misconceptions about sustainable living is that it requires sacrifice. In reality, many modern sustainable homes are designed to increase comfort rather than reduce it.</p>

        <p>
          Thoughtful architecture, passive cooling, natural ventilation and locally appropriate materials often
          create living environments that feel more comfortable and healthier than conventional alternatives. At
          Eco Village Sibang, sustainability and comfort are not opposing ideas. They work together.
        </p>

        <p>
          The goal is not to live with less. The goal is to live more intentionally. For many families, that means
          enjoying beautiful homes, meaningful community connections, greater access to nature and a lifestyle that
          feels aligned with the values they hope to pass on to their children.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mt-10 mb-3">Final Thoughts</h2>

        <p>
          For families considering Green School Bali, sustainable living often becomes part of a much larger
          conversation about lifestyle, community and quality of life. Eco Village Sibang offers one example of how
          these values can come together in practice.
        </p>

        <p>
          Its walkable location, family-focused environment, strong community and thoughtful approach to
          sustainability have made it a natural choice for many Green School families.
        </p>

        <p>
          Ultimately, sustainable living is not defined by a single building material or technology. It is
          reflected in how people live, connect, learn and grow together. For many families exploring life near
          Green School Bali, that journey begins with a school and evolves into a completely different way of
          living.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl font-bold text-primary mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <FAQAccordion faqs={faqs} idPrefix="sustainable-living-faq" client:load />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16 p-8 bg-card border border-border rounded-lg text-center">
        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-semibold text-primary mb-3">See sustainable living for yourself</h3>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-6">
          Get in touch to ask about availability at Villa Sungai and Villa Kailash, or schedule a viewing.
        </p>
        <a
          href="/inquire-now"
          class="inline-block px-8 py-3 bg-primary text-primary-foreground rounded-full font-semibold hover:bg-primary/90 transition-colors"
        >
          Inquire Now
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
